Before, we see examine anything from the data, write down what you expect the relationship would look like. Do you think people who record more exercise will have more or less BMI?

##I think people who record more exercise will have less BMI.

Now, letâs look at a simple correlation between these two variables. Recall that a correlation indicates how two variables move together. A negative correlation would imply that as one increases (say exercise), the other decreases (say BMI). A positive correlation in turn indicates that as one variable increases so does the other. Run the following code and tell me what the output indicates.

cor(exercise_data$Exercise, exercise_data$BMI)
[1] -0.06447185

##The output indicates that as exercise increases, BMI decreases.

Letâs explore this relationship visually. Make a scatterplot with exercise in the x axis and BMI in the y axis.

ggplot(exercise_data, aes(x = Exercise, y = BMI)) +
  geom_point()

What do you see?

##I see a dinosaur.

Yes, I tricked you. This is an example that comes from Alberto Cairo. It reinforces how important it is to look at your data.

Looking at presumed relationships without visualizing your data is a dangerous task, as this experiment neatly shows. Always look at your data; you donât want any Gorillas or Dinosaurs in your analyses.

Question 4

Add a layer that captures the overall relationship between these two variables using geom_smooth(). Use both the lm and gam methods.

ggplot(corruptDF, aes(x = HDI2017, y = CPI2017)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(corruptDF, aes(x = HDI2017, y = CPI2017)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "gam")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

What are the differences? Which one do you prefer?

##In the lm method, the line is straight. In the gam method, it is not.

##I think the graph is too cluttered. Another way to get these trends by region but in a way that would be more legible would be to use facet_wrap(~ region) .

Question 6

ggplot(corruptDF, aes(x = CPI2017, y = HDI2017, fill = region, color = region)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
